    topicCode: "OG-MOD-05-TOP-01",
    contentMd: `# Menstrual Disorders

Menstrual disorders represent the most frequent gynecological complaint, affecting 25-40% of reproductive-age women in India. Abnormal uterine bleeding (AUB), oligomenorrhea, and amenorrhea impact quality of life, fertility, and risk for serious underlying pathology. A systematic approach using the FIGO PALM-COEIN classification (Polyp, Adenomyosis, Leiomyoma, Malignancy, Coagulopathy, Ovulatory dysfunction, Endometrial, Iatrogenic, Not yet classified) streamlines diagnosis and management.

## Classification and Pathophysiology

**Amenorrhea** (absence of menses for ≥3 months) is classified as primary (no menarche by age 15) or secondary. Primary amenorrhea etiology includes gonadal dysgenesis, müllerian agenesis, androgen insensitivity, and pituitary-hypothalamic dysfunction. Secondary amenorrhea is predominantly functional (60-70%)—pregnancy, lactation, stress, weight loss, excessive exercise—with remaining cases due to ovarian pathology (PCOS, premature ovarian insufficiency) or pituitary dysfunction.

**Oligomenorrhea** (cycle length >35 days) often reflects anovulation secondary to PCOS, thyroid disorders, or hyperprolactinemia. **Menorrhagia** (heavy menstrual bleeding) may be organic (fibroids, adenomyosis, polyps) or functional (ovulatory dysfunction, coagulopathy). **Metrorrhagia** (intermenstrual bleeding) suggests local pathology or hormonal imbalance.

🎓 **FIGO Classification Value**: Systematically categorize AUB cause before initiating treatment; this guides targeted management and improves outcomes.

## Diagnostic Approach

The history prioritizes menarche age, cycle pattern, flow volume (sanitary products used, duration), associated symptoms (pain, systemic complaints), and contraceptive/medication use. Examination includes vital signs (assess for systemic illness, hemodynamic stability), abdominal examination, and speculum inspection. Bimanual palpation assesses uterine size, contour, and tenderness.

Investigations are directed by clinical findings. Pelvic ultrasound (transabdominal and transvaginal) is the first-line imaging for structural abnormalities. Hysteroscopy is reserved for cases suspicious for intrauterine pathology, missed miscarriage, or submucosal fibroid assessment. Laboratory tests (full blood count, coagulation profile, thyroid function, prolactin) are guided by presentation.

## Management by Category

**Amenorrhea Management** depends on etiology. Pregnancy must be excluded first. Thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) and prolactin levels guide endocrinological evaluation. Progesterone challenge (medroxyprogesterone 5-10 mg daily for 5 days) assesses estrogen adequacy. Withdrawal bleeding indicates adequate estrogen and intact outflow tract—typical in PCOS or mild ovulatory dysfunction. Absence suggests hypogonadal hypogonadism (low estrogen) or anatomical obstruction.

**Oligomenorrhea and Anovulation**: First-line management is lifestyle modification (weight loss if overweight, stress reduction, adequate sleep). Hormonally, combined oral contraceptives regularize cycles and protect endometrium in PCOS. Progestin-only regimens (medroxyprogesterone every 3 months, or levonorgestrel IUD) prevent endometrial hyperplasia while avoiding estrogen in contraindicated cases.

**Menorrhagia**: Heavy menstrual bleeding unresponsive to first-line medical therapy (NSAIDs, tranexamic acid, combined oral contraceptives, progestin-only regimens) warrants structural evaluation and consideration of interventional procedures. Levonorgestrel intrauterine system reduces bleeding by 60-90%. Endometrial ablation (chemical or thermal) permanently suppresses bleeding in selected cases. Myomectomy or hysterectomy is reserved for symptomatic structural disease with completed fertility.

💡 **Tranexamic Acid Efficacy**: 1.3 grams three times daily for 5 days during menses reduces menorrhagia by 30-50% with excellent safety profile—highly relevant in the Indian context with limited access to advanced interventions.

⚡ **Iron Supplementation**: Chronic menorrhagia frequently causes iron deficiency anemia, prevalent in Indian women. Concurrent iron supplementation (ferrous sulfate 200 mg daily) is often necessary alongside hemostatic therapy.

## Special Considerations in India

The PCPNDT Act 2021 mandates disclosure of fetal sex only at 19-20 weeks' scan; awareness of this informs ultrasound counseling. Menstrual disorders in adolescents are often managed conservatively given functional etiology predominance; however, persistent heavy bleeding warrants hematological evaluation to exclude inherited bleeding disorders.

🏥 **Clinical Pearl**: In amenorrheic women without apparent endocrinological disorder, assess for eating disorders or excessive exercise; these functional causes are increasingly recognized in urban Indian populations.

**References**: DC Dutta's Textbook of Obstetrics (9th ed) - Menstrual Disorders; Shaw's Textbook of Gynecology - Abnormal Uterine Bleeding; FIGO classification of abnormal uterine bleeding.`,
    estimatedMinutes: 10
