    topicCode: "OG-MOD-05-TOP-03",
    contentMd: `# Uterine Fibroids – Leiomyomas

Uterine fibroids (leiomyomas) are the most common benign tumors in women, found in 20-40% of reproductive-age women at ultrasound screening and in up to 80% at autopsy. Despite their high prevalence, only 20-25% are symptomatic. Fibroids arise from smooth muscle cells of the myometrium and may be classified by location as submucosal (0-2), intramural (3-4), or subserosal (5-7) using the FIGO classification. Understanding their presentation, evaluation, and management is crucial for obstetricians managing reproductive-age and perimenopausal women.

## Epidemiology and Pathophysiology

Fibroids are significantly more prevalent in Black African women compared to Caucasian women, with intermediate prevalence in Asian populations. Estrogen and progesterone dependence is established; fibroids regress post-menopausally. Growth factors (bFGF, TGF-β), angiogenesis, and altered myometrial contraction contribute to pathogenesis. Genetic factors (HMGA2, FH mutations) predispose; however, most fibroids are somatic mutations without inherited predisposition.

Submucosal fibroids (0-15% of cases) distort the endometrial cavity and cause menorrhagia, anemia, and infertility. Intramural fibroids (55-65%) may enlarge the uterus, cause dysmenorrhea, and rarely affect fertility unless >4 cm and distorting the cavity. Subserosal fibroids (20-40%) may be pedunculated; they rarely affect menstruation but cause bulk symptoms (pelvic pain, urinary frequency, bowel symptoms).

🎓 **FIGO Myoma Classification**: Submucosal (0-2), intramural (3-4), subserosal (5-7), and cervical variants must be distinguished; this informs management decisions.

## Clinical Presentation and Diagnosis

**Menorrhagia** is the most common symptom (30-40% of symptomatic women), presenting as heavy prolonged bleeding potentially causing iron deficiency anemia. Dysmenorrhea is common, particularly with submucosal or intramural fibroids. Bulk symptoms (urinary frequency, urgency, incomplete emptying; constipation; pelvic heaviness) occur with larger uteri or lower-lying fibroids. Infertility may be the presenting complaint in submucosal fibroids distorting the endometrial cavity.

Diagnosis is primarily ultrasound-based. Transvaginal ultrasound (TVS) is superior to transabdominal scanning for submucosal lesions; TVS alone evaluates the endometrial cavity adequately in most cases. MRI is reserved for complex cases: multiple fibroids, uncertain diagnosis, or preoperative planning for myomectomy. The FIGO classification guides imaging interpretation.

## Management Approach

**Observation**: Asymptomatic fibroids detected incidentally require no intervention; annual ultrasound is reasonable for large lesions to assess growth, but many remain stable. Symptomatic women should be offered treatment only after counseling regarding natural history and options.

**Medical Management**: NSAIDs reduce dysmenorrhea but minimally impact menorrhagia. Combined oral contraceptives and levonorgestrel IUD (52 mg) reduce menorrhagia by 30-50%, making them first-line medical therapy. Progestin-only regimens (medroxyprogesterone 150 mg IM quarterly) are alternatives. Gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) agonists (leuprolide, goserelin) shrink fibroids 30-60% but cause hypoestrogen symptoms; use is limited to 3-6 months preoperatively to reduce bleeding and blood loss during surgery. GnRH antagonists (elagolix, relugolix) offer better tolerability with sustained hemoglobin improvement.

💡 **Tranexamic Acid**: 1.3 grams three times daily for 5 days during menses reduces menorrhagia by 30-40% and is particularly useful in fibroids when surgery is declined or deferred.

**Interventional Procedures**: Hysteroscopic myomectomy is the procedure of choice for submucosal fibroids <4 cm in largest diameter, especially those protruding >50% into the cavity. Myomectomy (open abdominal or laparoscopic) preserves uterine function and is offered to women desiring fertility; however, recurrence rates are 15-35% at 5 years. Hysterectomy is definitive treatment for completed-family women with symptomatic, treatment-resistant fibroids.

**Newer Modalities**: Uterine artery embolization (UAE) is safe and effective, reducing fibroid volume by 30-50% and alleviating symptoms in 80-90% of cases; fertility preservation is variable. Focused ultrasound (MR-guided focused ultrasound surgery, MRgFUS) is emerging but limited in Indian settings due to cost and infrastructure. Selective progesterone receptor modulators (SPRMs) offer medical fibroid shrinkage but are not yet widely available in India.

⚡ **Fertility Considerations**: Submucosal fibroids <4 cm distorting the cavity should be resected in infertile women; intramural fibroids generally don't mandate intervention unless large (>4 cm) or severely distorting the cavity.

## Special Scenarios

**Fibroids and Pregnancy**: Fibroids rarely cause abortion spontaneously. Complications in pregnancy include red degeneration (pain, fever, nausea), preterm labor (large fibroids), placental abruption, and malpresentation. Most pregnancies progress normally; cesarean delivery is indicated only for malpresentation or obstruction to descent.

🏥 **Clinical Pearl**: In Indian women presenting with menorrhagia, always exclude fibroids despite symptom severity suggesting functional bleeding; structural lesions require targeted intervention.

**References**: DC Dutta's Textbook of Obstetrics (9th ed) - Fibroids; Shaw's Textbook of Gynecology - Benign Uterine Lesions; FIGO classification and management guidelines for uterine fibroids.`,
    estimatedMinutes: 10
