    topicCode: "OG-MOD-06-TOP-02",
    contentMd: `# Ovarian Tumors

Ovarian tumors encompass a diverse spectrum of benign, borderline, and malignant lesions. Benign ovarian cysts and tumors occur in 20-30% of reproductive-age women; most are asymptomatic and resolve spontaneously. However, malignant ovarian cancers represent a significant clinical challenge: ovarian cancer is the seventh most common cancer globally and the leading cause of gynecological cancer death. The goal is to identify suspicious lesions early while avoiding unnecessary intervention for benign findings.

## Classification and Epidemiology

**Histological Classification** divides ovarian tumors into three main categories: (1) **Epithelial tumors** (70-80% of ovarian tumors)—serous, mucinous, endometrioid, and clear-cell types; (2) **Germ-cell tumors** (15-20%)—including mature teratomas (dermoid cysts) and malignant variants; (3) **Sex cord-stromal tumors** (5%)—including granulosa cell and Sertoli-Leydig cell tumors.

**Benign Lesions**: Functional cysts (follicular, corpus luteum) are common in reproductive years and typically resolve within 1-2 menstrual cycles. Mature cystic teratomas (dermoid cysts) are benign and contain various tissue types (hair, bone, teeth). Serous and mucinous cystadenomas are epithelial benign tumors. Benign cysts <5 cm without suspicious imaging features have <1% malignancy risk.

**Malignant Tumors**: High-grade serous ovarian cancer is the most common malignant type, arising from fallopian tube epithelium and implanting on the ovary. Mucinous and endometrioid ovarian cancers, while less common, have better prognosis if confined to the ovary. Clear-cell ovarian cancer is associated with endometriosis and carries poor prognosis. Non-epithelial malignancies (germ-cell, sex cord-stromal) occur in younger women (20-40 years) and, though chemosensitive, present late.

🎓 **Ovarian Cancer Subtypes**: Recognizing histological subtypes is essential; they differ in pathogenesis, prognosis, and treatment response.

## Clinical Presentation and Risk Assessment

**Symptoms**: Most women with benign lesions are asymptomatic, detected incidentally on ultrasound. Malignant ovarian cancer presents insidiously; 70-75% present at stage III-IV. Symptoms include abdominal bloating, early satiety, persistent pelvic or abdominal pain, and urinary symptoms—often attributed to functional gastrointestinal complaints. Ovarian cancer screening, even in asymptomatic high-risk women, is not recommended given poor specificity of CA-125 and ultrasound, leading to high false-positive rates and unnecessary interventions.

**Risk Factors for Malignancy**:
- Age >50 years
- Postmenopausal status (malignancy risk in postmenopausal cysts is significantly higher)
- Complex cyst morphology on imaging
- Elevated CA-125 (>35 IU/mL) with clinical suspicion
- Family history of ovarian or breast cancer (BRCA mutations)
- Endometriosis (associated with endometrioid and clear-cell cancers)

## Diagnosis and Imaging

**Transvaginal Ultrasound (TVS)**: The first-line imaging modality. Benign features include thin walls, absence of solid components, and simple fluid content. Malignancy is suggested by complex morphology: thick septations, solid nodules, ascites, and irregular shape. TVS combined with clinical judgment and CA-125 (if indicated) guides triage.

**CA-125 Tumor Marker**: Elevated in 80-85% of advanced-stage ovarian cancers but only 50% of early-stage cancers. False elevations occur with benign conditions (menstruation, endometriosis, fibroids, PID), limiting specificity. The Ovarian Adnexal Reporting and Data System (O-RADS) combines imaging features with age and CA-125 to stratify malignancy risk.

**MRI and CT**: Reserved for characterization of complex cysts, staging of known malignancy, and surgical planning. MRI provides superior soft-tissue characterization; CT is less sensitive but more widely available.

## Management Approach

**Benign Cysts <5 cm**: Simple cysts require no follow-up. Mildly complex cysts (thin septations, small nodules) in reproductive-age women have <5% malignancy risk; TVS follow-up at 6-12 weeks and again at 1 year is reasonable. Mature teratomas (dermoid cysts) with macroscopic fat and calcifications are benign; surgery is elective, reserved for pain, torsion, or rupture.

**Benign Cysts 5-10 cm**: O-RADS scoring guides management. Low-risk lesions (O-RADS 1-2) require follow-up ultrasound at 1, 3, and 5 years. Intermediate-risk lesions (O-RADS 3) require closer monitoring. High-risk lesions (O-RADS 4-5) warrant surgical evaluation and likely resection.

💡 **Asymptomatic Postmenopausal Cysts**: Even simple cysts require surveillance due to elevated malignancy baseline. Follow-up at 4-6 weeks, then annually for 2 years is prudent.

**Suspicious Lesions/Malignancy**: Surgical staging via midline laparotomy (or staging laparoscopy in apparent early-stage disease) is performed by gynecological oncology. Optimal cytoreduction (residual disease <1 cm) to complete cytoreduction (no visible residual) improves survival. Platinum-based chemotherapy (carboplatin + paclitaxel ± bevacizumab) is standard adjuvant therapy for advanced disease. Newer agents (PARP inhibitors, immune checkpoint inhibitors) improve progression-free survival in selected populations.

## Special Considerations

**Fertility Preservation**: Young women with early-stage ovarian cancer are candidates for unilateral salpingo-oophorectomy (USO) and uterine preservation, enabling subsequent natural conception or assisted reproduction.

**Hereditary Ovarian Cancer**: BRCA1/BRCA2 mutations confer 40-50% lifetime ovarian cancer risk. Risk-reducing salpingo-oophorectomy at age 35-40 (after completion of childbearing) reduces ovarian cancer risk by 80-90%. Genetic testing and counseling are essential for high-risk families.

⚡ **Indian Context – Late-Stage Presentation**: Many Indian women present with advanced disease; emphasis on symptom awareness (particularly persistent abdominal distention and pain) may enable earlier detection.

🏥 **Clinical Pearl**: Persistent nonspecific abdominal symptoms in a woman >50 years warrant ovarian cancer screening; imaging is reasonable if clinical suspicion is high, even without significantly elevated CA-125.

**References**: DC Dutta's Textbook of Obstetrics (9th ed) - Ovarian Pathology; Shaw's Textbook of Gynecology - Ovarian Tumors; FIGO staging and treatment guidelines; O-RADS reporting system.`,
    estimatedMinutes: 11
